Apologies for the confusion. You can use the `cellRendererFramework` property instead of `cellRendererParams` to specify the component that should be used as the cell renderer. Here's an example:

1. Create a new component, let's call it CustomRendererComponent. Add your custom HTML template to the component's template file.

```
import { Component } from "@angular/core";
import { ICellRendererAngularComp } from "ag-grid-angular";

@Component({
    selector: "app-custom-renderer",
    template: `
    <div>
        {{ params.value }}
    </div>
    `
})
export class CustomRendererComponent implements ICellRendererAngularComp {
    public params: any;

    agInit(params: any): void {
        this.params = params;
    }

    refresh(params: any): boolean {
        return true;
    }
}
```

2. In your column definition, specify the component that should be used as the cell renderer.

```
columnDefs = [
    {
        headerName: "Custom Column",
        field: "customField",
        cellRendererFramework: CustomRendererComponent
    }
];
```

This will use your CustomRendererComponent as the cell renderer for the "Custom Column" field. The component will receive the cell value as a parameter, and can use it in its template.

To apply date filtering on ag-Grid columns, you can use the built-in ag-Grid date filter. Here is an example:

1. Define your column with a cell formatter for the date values

```
{
    headerName: "Date",
    field: "date",
    cellRenderer: (params) => {
        return new Date(params.value).toLocaleDateString();
    },
    filter: "agDateColumnFilter"
}
```

2. In the column definition, add the `filter` property and set it to `"agDateColumnFilter"`. This specifies that the built-in ag-Grid date filter should be used for this column.

Note: In the above example, `toLocaleDateString()` is used to format the date as a string. You can use your own date formatting method depending on your requirements.

With the above configuration, you will get a date filter in the column header dropdown. The filter allows the user to specify a date range, and the grid will display only those rows where the value in the "Date" column falls within the specified range.

The date filter also has additional options, such as filtering by "Equals", "Not Equals", etc. These options can be enabled by adding the `filterParams` property to the column definition, and setting the `comparator` property to `true`. For example:

```
{
    headerName: "Date",
    field: "date",
    cellRenderer: (params) => {
        return new Date(params.value).toLocaleDateString();
    },
    filter: "agDateColumnFilter",
    filterParams: {
        comparator: true
    }
}
```

This will add additional filter options to the date filter, such as "Equals", "Not Equals", etc.

You can use the built-in `toLocaleDateString()` method of the `Date` object to format a date object in the desired format. Here's an example code that shows how to format a date object as "3 Mar 2023":

```
const dateObj = new Date("2023-03-03");

const options = {
  day: "numeric",
  month: "short",
  year: "numeric"
};

const formattedDate = dateObj.toLocaleDateString("en-US", options);

console.log(formattedDate); // Output: "3 Mar 2023"
```

The `toLocaleDateString()` method takes two parameters - the first parameter specifies the locale to use (in this example, "en-US"), and the second parameter is an options object that specifies the date formatting options to use. 

In the options object, you can specify which parts of the date to include in the formatted string (day, month, year), and how to display them (short, long, numeric, etc). In this example, day is displayed as numeric, month as short, and year as numeric, resulting in the desired format of "3 Mar 2023".

To set styles on a div programmatically using JavaScript, you can use the JavaScript style property. 

Here's an example code that shows how to set the background color and font size of a div using JavaScript:

```javascript
const myDiv = document.querySelector("#myDiv");

myDiv.style.backgroundColor = "blue";
myDiv.style.fontSize = "24px";
```

In this example, `querySelector` is used to select the element with `id` "myDiv" and return a reference to it. 

Then, the `style` property of the div reference is used to set the background color and font size properties of the div. 

You can set any CSS property you like using the `style` property - just pass in the name of the CSS property as a string, and the value you want to set it to. Keep in mind that you need to use the JavaScript name of the CSS property, which may differ from the name you use in your CSS code (for example, `backgroundColor` instead of `background-color`).

The `webkitBoxOrient` CSS property is used to specify the orientation of a flexbox container. If you wish to display the content of the container vertically, you can set `webkitBoxOrient` property to "vertical".

Here's an example code that shows how to apply the `webkitBoxOrient` property to a parent container so that its child elements are displayed vertically:

```html
<div class="parent">
  <div class="child">Child 1</div>
  <div class="child">Child 2</div>
  <div class="child">Child 3</div>
</div>
```

```css
.parent {
  display: flex;
  display: -webkit-flex; /* for Safari compatibility */
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical; /* specify vertical orientation */
  -webkit-flex-direction: column; /* specify column orientation */
  flex-direction: column; /* specify column orientation */
}

.child {
  padding: 10px;
  background-color: lightblue;
  margin: 10px;
  width: 100px;
  text-align: center;
}
```

In this example, we have a parent container with the class `parent`, and three child elements.

We set the `display` property of the parent container to `flex`, and specify the `webkitBoxOrient` property to `vertical`, to display the child elements vertically. We also use the `flex-direction` property to specify the column orientation of the container, for compatibility with other browsers.

Finally, we add some CSS styles for the child elements, just to make them more visible.

This will display the child elements of the parent container vertically, as specified by the `webkitBoxOrient` property.

