Here's how you could use a loop to import the images instead of listing them all individually:

```
const icons = [];
for (let i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
  icons.push(require(`@/assets/img/icon${i}.png`));
}

class MyComponent extends Component {
  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        {icons.map((icon, index) => (
          <img key={index} src={icon} alt={`Icon ${index}`} />
        ))}
      </div>
    );
  }
}

export default MyComponent;
```

In this example, we're using a `for` loop to iterate over the numbers 1 to 10 and dynamically import each image using `require`. We're then storing these images in an array called `icons`. Finally, in the component's `render` method, we're using the `map` method to loop over the `icons` array and render each image as an `img` tag. We're also setting the `key` prop of each image to its index in the array, since React requires a unique key for each element in a list.

