You can create a JavaScript function to move the slider by updating the `left` and `width` CSS properties of the slider's process and dot elements respectively. Here's an example:

```javascript
function moveSlider(value) {
  // Get the slider elements
  const slider = document.querySelector('.vue-slider');
  const process = slider.querySelector('.vue-slider-process');
  const dot = slider.querySelector('.vue-slider-dot');
  const input = slider.querySelector('.vue-slider-sr-only');

  // Calculate the percentage based on the input value
  const min = parseInt(input.getAttribute('min'), 10);
  const max = parseInt(input.getAttribute('max'), 10);
  const percentage = ((value - min) / (max - min)) * 100;

  // Update the process and dot elements' style
  process.style.width = percentage + '%';
  dot.style.left = percentage + '%';

  // Update the input value
  input.value = value;
}

//Example: Move the slider to value 7
moveSlider(7);
```

Replace the value `7` in the `moveSlider(7)` function call with your desired slider value. The slider will then move to that value. Note that this approach directly manipulates the DOM, so any events or data bindings of the original slider component may not work as expected after moving the slider this way. You may adapt this method to suit your specific use case.

